Aponte-Rivera
Title: Modelling intrinsically disordered proteins with block polyampholytes
Project Description: Intrinsically disordered proteins (IDPs) are a class of proteins that are not folded in their healthy state. Instead, they adopt disordered and often fractal structures reminiscent of synthetic polymers. Modelling of electrostatic interactions in charged IDPs presents an important challenge, given the long-range nature, salt dependence, and pH dependence of these interactions. This project will use coarse-grained molecular dynamic simulations of model polyampholytes, polymers with both positive and negative charges, to study the role of electrostatic interactions in charged IDPs. Simulations of polyampholytes in different structural regimes will be carried out, and a method to map IDP properties to equivalent polyampholyte chains will be developed to understand the role of electrostatic interactions on IDPs.
Role of the REU Student: REU student will receive training in soft matter physics and coarse- grained molecular dynamic simulations. The student will carry out and analyze simulations of polyampholytes at different conditions.
Christian Aponte-Rivera, Ph.D. Assistant Professor, Department of Biomedical and Chemical Engineering. Website (https://aponte-rivera.org/)
Blatchley
Title: Characterizing extracellular matrix dynamics to build better organoids
Project Description: The near ubiquitous use of poorly defined, tumor-derived basement membrane extract (e.g., Matrigel) as a scaffold for 3D culture of organoids has severely limited the study of the role of extracellular matrix (ECM) compositional and mechanical dynamics on the growth of these biomimetic mini-organs. Notably, both ECM composition and mechanical properties can regulate a host of biological signaling pathways that control cell proliferation, differentiation, death, and morphology. We aim to: (1) better understand the properties of Matrigel at the cell and organoid scale, (2) characterize how the local microenvironment is remodeled, including by assessing the dynamics of cell-secreted proteins, and then (3) use this information to construct synthetic, phototunable ECM-mimetic materials to match the ECM dynamics of organoids cultured in Matrigel. These studies will enable us to more controllably and reproducibly grow organoids for use in translational medicine applications, such as disease modeling and drug testing.
